The '''Cenas tīrelis''' is a [[bog]] located in the municipalities of [[Mārupe Municipality|Marupe]], [[Babīte Municipality|Babite]] and [[Olaine Municipality|Olaine]], approximately 30 kilometers west of [[Riga]], [[Latvia]]. It is a [[Natura 2000]] protected site and one of Latvia's 261 [[Nature reserve|nature reserves]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daba.gov.lv/public/lat/iadt/dabas_liegumi/cenas_tirelis/|title=Dabas aizsardzības pārvalde|website=www.daba.gov.lv|access-date=2017-12-11}}</ref> It was formed 5000 years ago. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.atputasbazes.lv/lv/apskates_objekti/460_dabas_liegums_cenas_tirelis_purva_laipa_skatu_tornis/|title=Dabas liegums „Cenas tīrelis” (purva laipa, skatu tornis) :: Atputasbazes.lv|last=atputasbazes.lv|website=www.atputasbazes.lv|access-date=2017-12-11}}</ref>
The bog has a total size of 6,000 ha,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rigasmezi.lv/lv/mezi/par_meziem___fakti_/atputas_iespejas/?doc=1314|title=Cenas tīreļa purva taka, Rīgas meži|last=www.efumo.lv|website=www.rigasmezi.lv|access-date=2017-12-11}}</ref> mostly occupied by the nature reserve and an active [[peat extraction]] site. The Cenas tirelis bog is the second largest peatland in Latvia, after the [[Teiči Nature Reserve]], which has a total size of 19,779 ha. The "[[Skaista ezers]]", which is Latvian for "Beautiful Lake" is also located within the nature reserve.
In 2007 a [[trail]] of wooden planks was built in the southern area of the reserve. It leads from the end of the peat extraction area in a circle and has a total length of 5 kilometers. On the widest point away from the start, close to an old military road from [[World War I|WW1]], a [[Bird watching towers|bird watching tower]] and picnic tables can be found. Along the way, several information boards explain about the resident flora and fauna as well as about the peat industry in Latvia and the world in Latvian and English language.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.celotajs.lv/en/e/service/list/cenastirelis/all|title=Cenas tirelis - Specializations|last=Celotajs|first=LLTA Lauku|website=www.celotajs.lv|language=en|access-date=2017-12-11}}</ref> According to those information boards, peat is still used as energy source in Latvia and accounts for around 1% of the total [[energy mix]].
The reserve is home to several special of animals, including 10 protected bird species in Latvia. <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.latvia.travel/lv/apskates-vieta/cenas-tirela-purva-laipa|title=Cenas tīreļa purva laipa {{!}} Latvia Travel|website=www.latvia.travel|language=lv|access-date=2017-12-11}}</ref> It is also a common resting place for several [[Goose|geese]] and [[Crane (bird)|cranes]].
