[[File:Papire Masson.jpg|thumb|Jean Papire Masson, 1696 engraving by Jean Lubin.]] '''Jean Papire Masson''' {{lang-la|Papirius}}<ref>Also Jean Papyre Masson</ref> (1544, in [[Saint-Germain-Laval, Loire]] &ndash; 1611) was a French humanist historian, known also as a geographer, biographer, literary critic and jurist.
==Life== Masson was initially a [[Jesuit]], but left the Society.<ref name="JuvignyMaine1772">{{cite book|author1=Jean Antoine Rigoley de Juvigny|author2=François Grudé de La Croix Du Maine |author3=Antoine Du Verdier |author4=Bernard de La Monnoye |title=Bibliothèque Françoise De La Croix Du Maine |volume=2 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=v4FPAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA217 |year=1772 |location=Paris |publisher=Saillant & Nyon / Lambert |page=217}}</ref> He studied law at Angers under [[François Baudouin]] around 1570.<ref>{{cite book|author=Randall C. Zachman|title=John Calvin and Roman Catholicism: Critique and Engagement, Then and Now|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wSza_fU2yI4C&pg=PA34|accessdate=28 July 2012|date=1 September 2008|publisher=Baker Academic|isbn=978-0-8010-3597-5|pages=34–5}}</ref> He became close to the circle of [[Catherine de' Medici]], particularly to [[Carlo Boni]], and became professor of law at Angers, where Boni was bishop.<ref>{{cite book|author=Henry Heller|title=Anti-Italianism in Sixteenth-Century France|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LukUt8plM6gC&pg=PA118|accessdate=28 July 2012|year=2003|publisher=University of Toronto Press|isbn=978-0-8020-3689-6|page=118}}</ref> Later he was librarian to the Chevalier de Chiverny, was ''[[avocat]]'' to the [[Parlement of Paris]], and married.<ref name="JuvignyMaine1772"/>
==Works== He defended [[Antoine Matharel]] against [[François Hotman]].<ref>{{cite book|author=[[Quentin Skinner]]|title=The Foundations of Modern Political Thought: The Age of Reformation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dyzDnCLWJugC&pg=PA318|accessdate=28 July 2012|date=30 November 1978|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-29435-5|page=318|volume=2}}</ref> He may in fact have written much of Matharel's ''Responsio'' (1575) to Hotman's [[monarchomach]] work ''[[Francogallia]]''.<ref>{{cite book|author1=François Hotman|author2=Ralph E. Giesey|author3=J. H. M. Salmon|title=Francogallia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-pIMkpbKcs8C&pg=PA77|accessdate=28 July 2012|date=10 June 2010|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-15318-8|page=77}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Denis Pallier|title=Recherches sur l'imprimerie à Paris pendant la Ligue, 1585-1594|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FTNhhMw3n_kC&pg=PA46|accessdate=28 July 2012|year=1975|publisher=Librairie Droz|isbn=978-2-600-03432-6|page=46 note 29|language=fr}}</ref> The debate became a pamphlet war and slanging match.<ref>{{cite book|author=Paul-Alexis Mellet|title=Les Traités Monarchomaques: Confusion des Temps, Résistance Armée et Monarchie Parfaite, 1560-1600|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LwMurb1jCF8C&pg=PA340|accessdate=28 July 2012|year=2007|publisher=Librairie Droz|isbn=978-2-600-01139-6|pages=340–1|language=fr}}</ref>
The Latin life of [[John Calvin]] attributed to Masson had a reputation in its time as fair-minded.<ref>{{cite book|author=Irena Dorota Backus|title=Life Writing in Reformation Europe: Lives of Reformers by Friends, Disciples and Foes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_90Q5BAnTEwC&pg=PA220|accessdate=28 July 2012|year=2008|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|isbn=978-0-7546-6055-2|page=220}}</ref>
Masson discovered a manuscript of [[Agobard]] in 1604, and edited it.<ref>{{cite book|author=Courtney M. Booker|title=Past Convictions: The Penance of Louis the Pious and the Decline of the Carolingians|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=afy8_EmYZMUC&pg=PA321|accessdate=28 July 2012|date=12 August 2009|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|isbn=978-0-8122-4168-6|page=321}}</ref>
